<div class="lang-en">
<section id="overview">
  <h2>Why the Bedroom Matters in Feng Shui</h2>
  <p>In <a href="/fengshui/">feng shui</a>, the bedroom is the most important room in the house. You spend roughly one-third of your life there &mdash; sleeping, resting, and being at your most vulnerable. The quality of Qi (<span class="chinese-char">氣</span>) in your bedroom directly affects sleep quality, health, intimate relationships, and the energy you carry into each day.</p>
  <p>Classical feng shui texts describe the bedroom as a <strong>yin space</strong> &mdash; it should be calm, dark, quiet, and restorative, in contrast to the yang energy of kitchens, offices, and living rooms. When yin and yang are reversed (a bedroom that is overstimulating, cluttered, or too bright), the occupant's health and relationships suffer.</p>
  <p>The principles below come from classical Form School (<span class="chinese-char">形勢派</span>) and Compass School (<span class="chinese-char">理氣派</span>) feng shui, adapted for modern living spaces. They apply regardless of whether your home is a studio flat or a detached house.</p>
</section>
</div>
<div class="lang-tc">
<section id="overview">
  <h2>為何臥室在風水中至關重要</h2>
  <p>在<a href="/fengshui/">風水</a>學中，臥室是家中最重要的房間。人生約三分之一的時間在此度過——睡眠、休息，也是最脆弱的時刻。臥室中氣（<span class="chinese-char">氣</span>）的品質直接影響睡眠質素、健康、親密關係，以及每天帶出的精力。</p>
  <p>傳統風水典籍將臥室描述為<strong>陰性空間</strong>——應該安靜、昏暗、寧謐、有助恢復，與廚房、辦公室和客廳的陽氣形成對比。當陰陽顛倒（臥室過於刺激、雜亂或太亮）時，居住者的健康和感情便會受損。</p>
  <p>以下原則源自傳統形勢派（<span class="chinese-char">形勢派</span>）和理氣派（<span class="chinese-char">理氣派</span>）風水，並針對現代居住空間加以調適。無論您住的是開放式公寓還是獨棟住宅，這些原則同樣適用。</p>
</section>
</div>
